===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

{{Han compound|水|alt1=氵|㕣|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p|t1=water}}. The character originally referred to the edge of a river, and by extension, it came to represent the idea of "following along" or "accompanying."<ref>Digital Shinjigen 2017</ref>

====References====
{{reflist}}

===Etymology 1===
The same word as {{och-l|緣|id=1|to go along}}. Cognate with {{och-l|緣|id=2|hem; border on garment}}, which is the [[exopassive]] of {{och-l|沿|lit=what is followed/follows}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

Possibly related to {{w|Proto-Tai language|Proto-Tai}}, compare {{cog|th|เลียน||to mimic}}, or from {{w|Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan}}; compare {{cog|lus|zeelᴸ||to walk along, a road along a hillside}} and {{cog|kac|mə³¹-jan³³||flow along a cliff}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}); nevertheless, Schuessler finds Middle Chinese descendant's rounded element difficult to reconcile phonologically with these items and proposes also a derivation from {{och-l|由}}.

